    <h2>Statistics, Context, and the Problem of Eras</h2>

    <p>Messi has the advantage in numbers — clearly. But the context matters enormously. In Maradona's era, matches were fewer, the game was more defensive, and Serie A in the 1980s was saturated with tactical marking that made individual scoring output almost impossible to compare with the high-tempo, space-rich football of the 2000s and 2010s. Maradona's Napoli years, in particular, were played in a league specifically designed to neutralise his influence.</p>

    <p>Despite that, what stands out about Messi is not merely the volume of his goals — extraordinary as that is — but the dual nature of his contribution. He is simultaneously the most dangerous finisher and the most creative provider of his generation. That combination is genuinely unprecedented.</p>

